# G094 Tree-Sitter Cognitive Capability Demo
#
# This script demonstrates how an LLM agent can use tree-sitter
# capabilities from Edict to parse and analyze source code.
#
# Usage:
#   AGENTC_BUILD_DIR=<build_dir> ./build/edict/edict -e "$(cat demo.edict)"

# --- Setup: Load the C parser ---
'c treesitter.load!

# --- Example 1: Parse and inspect C source ---
'c "int main() { return 42; }" treesitter.parse! @ast

# Show the root node type
ast.type .
# => translation_unit

# Show JSON representation
ast to_json! .
# => {"type":"translation_unit","start_byte":"0",...}

# --- Example 2: Structural diff ---
# An agent can compare two versions of source code
# to understand what changed at the AST level.
'c "int x;" "int x; int y;" treesitter.diff! @diff

# Show the diff as JSON
diff to_json! .
# => [{"kind":"added","type":"declaration",...}]

# --- Example 3: Parse Python ---
'python treesitter.load!
'python "def hello():\n    return 42" treesitter.parse! @pyast
pyast.type .
# => module

# --- Example 4: List all loaded languages ---
treesitter.list! to_json! .
# => ["c","python"]

# --- Summary ---
# The treesitter builtin capsule provides three cognitive operations:
#   treesitter.load!   — load a language parser
#   treesitter.parse!  — parse source code into a navigable AST
#   treesitter.diff!   — structural diff between two source versions
#
# An agent uses these instead of regex-based reasoning when it needs
# precise code structure understanding, e.g.:
#   - "What functions were added in this commit?"
#   - "Does this code contain a return statement?"
#   - "Where is the variable 'x' declared?"
